European inflation declined in food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the tedious growth in the price of foodstuffs.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only probably gave a 3 percent -- the Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "have to negotiate" on inflation so that it will not later have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, beat the twelve-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation occurred in the euro area as a result of the galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat-term contributions increased by 88 per cent and soy-quotation had reached its maximum level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 black gold the barrel by now last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will fall from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent, instead by 2009 it will decrease to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, it is expected that during 2008 the ECB will double the interest rates.
