In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, first of all, because of the improper application of antibiotics.
The conditions of hygiene prevailing in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the department-medical chief of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
A contact with MRSA has recently been diagnosed in the trauma department of the Hospital János.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital early in the year.
A serious car accident wound was released from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital as a result of the infection with MRSA and since then there has been no significant surgical intervention by the presence of the bacteria in her body.
Up to 10 December of this year, they have been registered in the Nosocomialis Surveillance National System 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents - said Karolina Böröcz, a medical chief department of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded in hospitals, although no information is available.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, methicillin-oxaclin-resistant.
One third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, amygdalitis, skin infections, wounds) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is excessively or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that usually react well to antibiotics become bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and quickly contaminate in inadequate hospital conditions.
They may cause serious hospital infections, such as injuries or septicemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to elderly or to persons with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic-resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff take care of them in rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients who are hospitalized are previously examined to check the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not even possible to prevent infection in all cases.
You're not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA's hospital infections in most cases, however, the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - Karolina Böröcz says.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the patients taking MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most of the cases come out in public light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the department chief-doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union is rigorously commending the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance from occurring, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples is even less frequent in the case of travelling patients or in the primary care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saving with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, but also in this sense there are significant deficiencies in hospitals.
MRSA was infected by drop transmission and direct contact between individuals, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately you can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in less favourable economic hospitals you save with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater likelihood for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the infection of the pathogen may be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
Treatment of contact with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
It appears that the program is successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
