Fucker and six percent Hungarian
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime post-2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries in the world discuss the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on the particulars between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to reach the agreement that compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020 the emissions of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major issue of the conference is whether industrialised countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are prepared to provide material and technological assistance to countries in need.
A further agreement was reached on aid for developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a board of directors consisting of 16 members, probably within the Global Environment Facility of the UN (GEF) - writes the "Piac is Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent to 2020, with respect to the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the "after 2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the other major developed regions in the world and developing countries are also willing to take commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 per cent, in which the 15 EU Member States then committed to achieving an 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 per cent the greenhouse gas emissions from the period 1985-87, which our country will meet - notes the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
It is a great deal of what is at stake in Bali, since within two years it will be necessary to sign the long-term international climate policy agreement, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed by after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the United Nations International Scientific Partnership dealing with climate change, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
As a result, emissions reduction would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, which according to scientists would have unsurpassed and irreversible consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of filmed actions in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: Special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These tapes made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general body of Kandahar operations, then sent to London to be loaded to the Internet.
Political message is inevitable
139 recordings from air force soldiers have already been loaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "Headquarters Defence" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the British Community (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence, they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs virtually nothing compared to conventional recruiting television spots - told the BBC the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason to be of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans set up a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the tapes carefully edited and censored, there are also amateur videos in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, officers talk as much as possible about losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet from the battle camps in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army has only recently been taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way to recruit with video shoots, which can be downloaded for free, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can be placed directly instead of the soldiers.
