After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million file documents, stored on 27 km of shelves at Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not available here only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of an old victim or of his rights.
The 11 States responsible for their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to the researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratifying this agreement by all States has been completed, openness has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to make searches " particularly about the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers " , explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, had opposed the opening to the public of these nominee documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected to compulsory work and, where appropriate, to give them proof of their detention, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
" There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected of these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Centre on AntiSemitism at the Technical University of Berlin in 2006.
