Congress approves the transposition of Mifid, which entered into force 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary process, which ended today with the Congress's vote on amendments to the draft in the Senate, the Government has submitted to the public hearing the rules of procedure to be developed by the new law, with the aim that they both enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and Senators to negotiate and consent to the best regulation in order to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activity of entities for markets to function efficiently.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, implies the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the various European Union supervisors.
The new legislation will provide financial advisory services to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firm (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio managers.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the implementation of operations on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment service companies to disclose information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management on the market and requires them to keep a record of all the operations they perform, to facilitate the monitoring by the NCMV.
A number of amendments were incorporated through the Congressional Economic Commission, including the fact that debt titrated is considered as a "complex" financial instrument given its high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated with the debt of high-risk U.S. mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delineate the functions that graduates can develop in economic and business 30 years after the actual decree defining professional functions reserved for economists was passed in 1977.
