Venus: Twin brother from Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most like the Earth, something that had not been raised until now. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and raisins in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For the past three decades, researchers had suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new tests: discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays are silent at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, had originated the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it's not like this: if I ever had life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface there are temperatures of 500°C, oscillating in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Perhaps Venus is a "diabolic" gem on Earth, but it's still a twin," said Russell.
The main objective of the mission "Venus Express" is to answer the question why Venus, so much like the Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
As since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step in the investigation of Venus.
The latest results of the research to be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to researchers' opinion, not only emphasize Venus' uniqueness in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with the Earth than we had assumed," says ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds of wind flows in the high earth's atmospheric layers of poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost so large.
This planet also called the dawn star or the evening star orbits around the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not much like the Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed in the same conditions.
On the two planets water had been aggregated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it was disounded in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
